Hard to say. One of the benefits of using models like this is that it would
let you understand the associations between the latent distributional
parameters, after netting out the sampling error. Since the sampling errors
are approximately uncorrelated, I would expect that the correlations
between the parameters will be stronger than the correlation between
observed effect size estimates (i.e., the observed correlations would be
attenuated).


> While I am still unsure if it is the an appropriate approach to consider,
> I further explored the comparability between the results in separate models
> and a model that includes the measure (i.e., means or SD) as a moderator.
> For obtaining variance-covariance matrices, I specified the clusters per
> group id and measure (rather than group id only). The main results of this
> model are exactly identical to the separate models' outputs. What seems to
> differ and increase substantially are the heterogeneity results (e.g., Q
> stats, sigma at different levels), which I assume is due to the different
> metrics pooled together.
>

The Q statistics won't be very interpretable in a model like this. To do a
true bivariate model, you should probably let the random effects differ by
measure type:
random = list(~ measure | StudyID, ~ measure | OutcomeID),
struct = c("UN","UN"),

Not allowing the random effects to differ by measure type will mean that
the heterogeneity estimates will be pooled across measures, making them
quite hard to interpret. If you allow the random effects to differ, then I
would expect the variance component estimates from each model should be
fairly similar to the variance components estimated from separate models
for each measure type.

What are your thoughts on moving forward? Considering the subtle trend we
> observed in the visual exploration, the identical results from both
> separate and multivariate models, together with our lack of familiarity and
> confidence in multivariate model approaches, my way to go is to stick with
> separate models. While this might be the most reasonable approach at this
> stage, I am not comfortable if it allows us to include the use of
> benchmarks that consider both the pooled mean and SD together.
>
>
>
Based on this explanation, I think moving forward with separate models
seems appropriate and reasonable. The multivariate model that I'm
suggesting is not by any means standard or widely used--it's just a
suggestion for what seems to me to be a nuanced way to approach modeling
your data. I doubt that peer reviewers would demand going with a
multivariate analysis, and any statistical analysis is going to be
provisionary, after all. Future researchers (including future you!) could
always try to further refine whatever analysis you present.


